If A^{p,q} is a bigraded object of \mathscr {A} such that






    A^{p,q}=0 except for a finite number of pairs (p,q), and





    A^{p,q}=0 for p+q \neq  n






then we define two n-opposite filtrations of A= \sum _{p,q}A^{p,q} by setting

501Equationhodge-theory-ii-equation-1.2.4.1hodge-theory-ii-equation-1.2.4.1.xml1.2.4.1hodge-theory-ii-1.2.4         F^p(A)         =  \sum _{p' \geqslant  p} A^{p',q'}       \tag{1.2.4.1}       

502Equationhodge-theory-ii-equation-1.2.4.2hodge-theory-ii-equation-1.2.4.2.xml1.2.4.2hodge-theory-ii-1.2.4          \overline {F}^q(A)         =  \sum _{q' \geqslant  q} A^{p',q'}.       \tag{1.2.4.2}       

We have

503Equationhodge-theory-ii-equation-1.2.4.3hodge-theory-ii-equation-1.2.4.3.xml1.2.4.3hodge-theory-ii-1.2.4          \operatorname {Gr} _F^p \operatorname {Gr} _{ \overline {F}}^q(A)         = A^{p,q}.       \tag{1.2.4.3}

html:ol.html:li:
If F and \overline {F} are n-opposite, and if we set
          \begin {cases}           A^{p,q} = 0           & \text {for }p+q \neq  n          \\ A^{p,q} = F^p(A) \cap \overline {F}^q(A)           & \text {for }p+q=n          \end {cases}       
then A is the direct sum of the A^{p,q}, and F and \overline {F} come from the bigrading A^{p,q} of A by the procedure of .

